00:24:02,459 --> 00:24:03,400
- Yeah.
- What?

507
00:24:03,425 --> 00:24:04,796
The Nissan-bloody-Juke.

508
00:24:04,882 --> 00:24:05,804
Exactly.

509
00:24:05,867 --> 00:24:08,051
I don't want to look
at that now.

510
00:24:08,084 --> 00:24:10,326
No, exactly. Or the Dodge Dart.

511
00:24:10,426 --> 00:24:13,287
Well, what child's gonna
say, "Oh, Daddy!"

512
00:24:13,334 --> 00:24:16,560
Daddy, let's go and look at the
40-year-old Dart in the museum"?

513
00:24:16,701 --> 00:24:17,912
Nobody is!

514
00:24:17,943 --> 00:24:19,248
It's true that car design

515
00:24:19,273 --> 00:24:20,536
has become so dreary lately.

516
00:24:20,637 --> 00:24:22,018
And I think part of it,

517
00:24:22,063 --> 00:24:23,987
it's almost as if
the people who design cars

518
00:24:24,064 --> 00:24:25,612
don't actually like
cars that much.

519
00:24:25,682 --> 00:24:27,515
Exactly. But they did then.
You can tell.

520
00:24:27,546 --> 00:24:30,206
There was a Cuda in there
next to a Plymouth Fury,

521
00:24:30,271 --> 00:24:33,093
and I just stood for about an
hour, just soaking them in.

522
00:24:33,203 --> 00:24:35,878
I saw a 1966 Cadillac.

523
00:24:35,944 --> 00:24:37,520
We've got a picture
of it here. Look.

524
00:24:37,644 --> 00:24:39,245
Now, what I like about this

525
00:24:39,354 --> 00:24:41,183
is that the bloke
who designed the bonnet,

526
00:24:41,223 --> 00:24:43,059
he... the grill. "I've finished
with the bonnet."

527
00:24:43,083 --> 00:24:43,792
I'll do the grill."

528
00:24:43,817 --> 00:24:45,460
But he didn't tell
the blokes doing the wings,

529
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:48,597
and they kept going, so it
goes like another foot.

530
00:24:48,706 --> 00:24:51,167
No, but this is fantastic
with a fantastic-looking car.

531
00:24:51,214 --> 00:24:53,269
The Buick Riviera, they had
one of those in there.

532
00:24:53,321 --> 00:24:55,097
- Look at that!
- That is glorious!

533
00:24:55,159 --> 00:24:56,172
I had one of those

534
00:24:56,222 --> 00:24:57,605
as a toy when I was little.

535
00:24:57,630 --> 00:24:59,480
If you put your finger
over the back window,

536
00:24:59,543 --> 00:25:01,112
it flashed its lights.

537
00:25:01,278 --> 00:25:02,558
And you just look and you go,

538
00:25:02,611 --> 00:25:05,175
"How can Buick have gone
from doing that

539
00:25:05,260 --> 00:25:07,261
"in, what, 30-40 years,
to doing this,

540
00:25:07,286 --> 00:25:09,112
whatever this brown..."
Look at...

541
00:25:09,644 --> 00:25:10,808
How have they done that?!

542
00:25:10,941 --> 00:25:12,480
And it's the same as Chevrolet.

543
00:25:12,534 --> 00:25:14,600
There was an Impala
in there, 1960.

544
00:25:14,625 --> 00:25:17,193
Look at that!
That is exciting not moving!

545
00:25:17,230 --> 00:25:19,487
That's a Chevy
Impala from the '60s.

546
00:25:19,558 --> 00:25:21,167
Let's have a look at one
from today.

547
00:25:21,253 --> 00:25:22,713
Oh, for God's sake!

548
00:25:22,925 --> 00:25:25,043
How do they even have the
nerve to call that an Impala?

549
00:25:25,067 --> 00:25:25,935
Because it isn't one.

550
00:25:25,960 --> 00:25:27,886
I was looking at a Corvette,

551
00:25:27,939 --> 00:25:28,987
a '70s Corvette.

552
00:25:29,038 --> 00:25:30,138
That's the C3 model,

553
00:25:30,163 --> 00:25:31,308
if you're a Corvette nerd.

554
00:25:31,333 --> 00:25:32,568
This was a car that was driven

555
00:25:32,630 --> 00:25:34,279
by all of the astronauts.

556
00:25:34,411 --> 00:25:36,847
- Exactly.
- And Dirk Diggler.

557
00:25:36,974 --> 00:25:38,114
Yep.

558
00:25:38,177 --> 00:25:39,825
Ah, so it's a car

559
00:25:39,851 --> 00:25:41,974
for porn stars and astronauts.

560
00:25:42,019 --> 00:25:44,254
- What a strapline!
- What car is there today

561
00:25:44,279 --> 00:25:46,239
that could be driven by
porn stars and astronauts?

562
00:25:46,310 --> 00:25:48,358
- There isn't one.
- An Alfa!

563
00:25:48,418 --> 00:25:50,723
An Alfa?!

564
00:25:51,044 --> 00:25:53,072
Actually, he's right!

565
00:25:53,146 --> 00:25:55,932
No, astronauts
have to get there.

566
00:25:55,974 --> 00:25:57,372
He's right! That's exactly

567
00:25:57,397 --> 00:25:59,659
- what the Quadriplegio is!
- No!

568
00:25:59,733 --> 00:26:02,741
This is for porn stars and astronauts,
which is what I am.

569
00:26:02,843 --> 00:26:04,307
Now, I would like to have

570
00:26:04,358 --> 00:26:07,543
a conversation about
the Nürburgring.

571
00:26:07,772 --> 00:26:09,092
- Go on.
- Because this is important.

572
00:26:09,116 --> 00:26:10,646
Last year, I was delighted.

573
00:26:10,686 --> 00:26:12,475
The people who run
the Nürburgring in Germany,

574
00:26:12,499 --> 00:26:15,285
they said they were gonna
ban car manufacturers

575
00:26:15,436 --> 00:26:17,327
from setting lap records there.

576
00:26:17,405 --> 00:26:19,889
Sorry, why were you
delighted about that?

577
00:26:19,943 --> 00:26:21,460
Because that's
an excellent idea.

578
00:26:21,577 --> 00:26:23,968
If you make a car
that is excellent

579
00:26:24,038 --> 00:26:25,537
for doing a fast lap
of the Nürburgring,

580
00:26:25,561 --> 00:26:28,164
it would be useless as a car
everywhere else in your life.

581
00:26:28,225 --> 00:26:30,405
It's like... It's like
setting your house up

582
00:26:30,444 --> 00:26:31,483
to play Laser Quest.

583
00:26:31,508 --> 00:26:34,237
It will be brilliant
for playing Laser Quest,

584
00:26:34,280 --> 00:26:35,617
but it'll be rubbish
for a dinner party

585
00:26:35,641 --> 00:26:36,804
because it's full of lasers,

586
00:26:36,881 --> 00:26:38,530
darkness, fog
and music that goes...

587
00:26:39,676 --> 00:26:40,554
and people running around

588
00:26:40,593 --> 00:26:41,953
thinking that they're
in Star Wars.

589
00:26:42,022 --> 00:26:43,413
Or you could get a dog...

590
00:26:43,491 --> 00:26:45,405
You could train a dog
as an attack dog,

591
00:26:45,407 --> 00:26:47,944
which is fantastic
if you own a scrapyard

592
00:26:48,022 --> 00:26:49,358
and you need
the dog to guard it,

593
00:26:49,386 --> 00:26:52,811
but take it home as a pet,
it will eat your children.

594
00:26:52,928 --> 00:26:53,851
It's completely useless.

595
00:26:53,875 --> 00:26:54,600
That's what happens

596
00:26:54,625 --> 00:26:56,905
when you set a car up
for the Nürburgring.

597
00:26:56,940 --> 00:26:58,741
This isn't really
a conversation, James.

598
00:26:58,813 --> 00:27:01,554
No, I think we've accidentally
turned down Rant Lane this week.

599
00:27:01,694 --> 00:27:02,990
Well, there's more.

600
00:27:03,014 --> 00:27:04,100
- He's off again.
- No, no.

601
00:27:04,125 --> 00:27:06,602
But the thing is,
the bad news in all this

602
00:27:06,639 --> 00:27:07,874
is that they've decided

603
00:27:07,939 --> 00:27:09,805
that they will allow
car manufacturers

604
00:27:09,835 --> 00:27:11,397
to set lap records again.

605
00:27:11,422 --> 00:27:12,327
Well, that's good.

606
00:27:12,410 --> 00:27:13,577
- No, it's bad!
- OK.

607
00:27:13,608 --> 00:27:15,630
Think of the cars
that have come out recently

608
00:27:15,655 --> 00:27:17,044
that we've driven
that have been developed

609
00:27:17,068 --> 00:27:18,877
so that they would go fast
around the Nürburgring.

610
00:27:18,901 --> 00:27:20,802
BMW M4 GTS,

611
00:27:20,874 --> 00:27:22,908
you can't deny it,
it's a terrible car.

612
00:27:22,963 --> 00:27:24,964
Nissan GT-R,
the Track Edition,

613
00:27:24,989 --> 00:27:26,522
that is a terrible car.

614
00:27:26,577 --> 00:27:29,874
Even SEAT...
the SEAT Leon Cupra 280,

615
00:27:29,968 --> 00:27:32,462
that's got a hatchback record for
going around the Nürburgring,

616
00:27:32,514 --> 00:27:33,530
and it's rubbish!

617
00:27:33,591 --> 00:27:35,843
The Nürburgring ruins cars.

618
00:27:35,905 --> 00:27:37,616
I'm developing an app
for the smart phone

619
00:27:37,679 --> 00:27:39,002
called Bomb The Nürburgring

620
00:27:39,027 --> 00:27:40,894
where you guide
a Dornier 17 over it

621
00:27:41,007 --> 00:27:42,448
and blow it up.

622
00:27:42,538 --> 00:27:44,413
What are you doing
on this programme?

623
00:27:44,438 --> 00:27:45,694
Talking sense!

624
00:27:45,756 --> 00:27:47,557
Good question.
I don't know.

625
00:27:47,644 --> 00:27:50,513
We have this old woman who
has a baking show in Britain.

626
00:27:50,552 --> 00:27:51,826
She's called Mary Berry.

627
00:27:51,912 --> 00:27:53,873
It would be...
You probably know her.

628
00:27:53,966 --> 00:27:55,107
It's probably the same

629
00:27:55,162 --> 00:27:57,187
as her saying, "I hate cakes!"

630
00:27:57,208 --> 00:27:58,162
Yes.

631
00:27:58,206 --> 00:27:59,552
Mary Berry would agree with me,

632
00:27:59,606 --> 00:28:01,200
because if she made a cake

633
00:28:01,232 --> 00:28:02,993
that had been developed
on the Nürburgring,

634
00:28:03,029 --> 00:28:05,662
someone would put
fried onions on the top

635
00:28:05,708 --> 00:28:07,724
and completely ruin it.
You'd have a Victoria sponge

636
00:28:07,748 --> 00:28:10,100
with onion on the top
for no reason!

637
00:28:10,201 --> 00:28:11,677
James, you know
you're weird, don't you?

638
00:28:11,701 --> 00:28:13,857
That's not weird. That's
the most sensible thing

639
00:28:13,958 --> 00:28:15,224
that's ever been said
on this show.

640
00:28:15,248 --> 00:28:16,833
- You are weird.
- I'm not weird.

641
00:28:16,943 --> 00:28:18,880
He is weird! We were coming
through the airport

642
00:28:18,963 --> 00:28:20,693
here the other day,
coming through Chicago,

643
00:28:20,771 --> 00:28:22,849
and he went,
"Jeremy, smell my jacket."

644
00:28:22,896 --> 00:28:24,029
He said what?!

645
00:28:24,099 --> 00:28:25,169
- Yeah.
- He did.

646
00:28:25,224 --> 00:28:26,882
He said, "Smell my jacket."
I said, "Why?"

647
00:28:26,904 --> 00:28:29,352
He said, "Because it smells
of old record players."

648
00:28:29,412 --> 00:28:32,201
- Mate, that is weird.
- But it did!

649
00:28:32,466 --> 00:28:34,474
You know record players
don't smell of anything?

650
00:28:34,591 --> 00:28:36,002
They do. Old ones do.

651
00:28:36,027 --> 00:28:37,396
They smell of old
record players.

652
00:28:37,474 --> 00:28:39,129
Who knows what they smell like?

653
00:28:39,201 --> 00:28:40,662
- I'd like us...
- The decaying...

654
00:28:40,697 --> 00:28:42,032
I'd like us to move it on

655
00:28:42,037 --> 00:28:43,662
because it's getting scary now.

656
00:28:43,716 --> 00:28:45,099
That's not the record player!

657
00:28:45,124 --> 00:28:46,716
We'll have another...
What are you on about?

658
00:28:46,740 --> 00:28:48,260
Does anybody have
an old record player,

659
00:28:48,294 --> 00:28:49,356
or anything old electrical?

660
00:28:49,380 --> 00:28:50,404
They smell, don't they?

661
00:28:50,429 --> 00:28:52,419
Has anybody ever smelled
an old record player?

662
00:28:52,451 --> 00:28:54,232
Really? You think you have?

663
00:28:54,443 --> 00:28:56,079
You've smelled an old...

664
00:28:56,169 --> 00:28:58,146
God, strewth!

665
00:28:59,755 --> 00:29:02,615
Did it have a wax cylinder on
it, your old record player?

666
00:29:02,716 --> 00:29:05,419
They smell like old plastic
and warm rubber.

667
00:29:05,591 --> 00:29:06,661
Yeah, exactly.

668
00:29:06,724 --> 00:29:09,460
That smells like a party at James's house.
special... is that..

669
00:29:11,154 --> 00:29:13,716
You're actually talking
to Thomas Edison there.

670
00:29:16,300 --> 00:29:17,700
In person.

671
00:29:17,818 --> 00:29:19,102
Well done, sir.

672
00:29:19,294 --> 00:29:20,578
Now, as we're told

673
00:29:20,633 --> 00:29:23,466
almost every day
these days, really,

674
00:29:23,521 --> 00:29:26,576
the world's coral reefs
are all dying.

675
00:29:26,732 --> 00:29:29,591
And we're told that this
is the fault of the car.

676
00:29:29,646 --> 00:29:31,849
Well, since we host a car show,

677
00:29:31,919 --> 00:29:34,460
we thought it would be
our duty and responsibility

678
00:29:34,591 --> 00:29:36,396
to do something about it.

679
00:29:43,865 --> 00:29:47,706
Here in the Caribbean,
all appears to be well.

680
00:29:47,831 --> 00:29:49,765
But under
the shimmering blue sea,

681
00:29:49,862 --> 00:29:53,307
there's just miles
and miles of sand.

682
00:29:54,640 --> 00:29:56,589
It's an underwater desert.

683
00:29:58,175 --> 00:30:00,050
And even when
you do find a reef,

684
00:30:00,159 --> 00:30:03,104
most of the coral
is dead or dying.

685
00:30:07,143 --> 00:30:08,451
Thirty-eight years ago,

686
00:30:08,511 --> 00:30:10,386
the local government sank a ship

687
00:30:10,425 --> 00:30:13,448
to encourage the coral
to come back.

688
00:30:14,225 --> 00:30:16,003
And it's working.

689
00:30:16,227 --> 00:30:19,249
It's already an oasis of life.

690
00:30:21,165 --> 00:30:24,202
And that gave us an idea.

691
00:30:24,959 --> 00:30:28,115
Why use a ship as the hub
or your coral reef?

692
00:30:28,171 --> 00:30:30,976
Why not use cars?
There are millions of them.

693
00:30:31,171 --> 00:30:33,585
So that's exactly what we've
done. We've got five cars.

694
00:30:33,671 --> 00:30:35,445
And rather than go
through all the expense

695
00:30:35,470 --> 00:30:37,347
and complication
of recycling them,

696
00:30:37,452 --> 00:30:39,366
we've stripped them,
taken the engines out,

697
00:30:39,476 --> 00:30:41,905
removed the paint, and they're
ready to go in the sea.

698
00:30:42,007 --> 00:30:43,874
This really does
make perfect sense,

699
00:30:43,944 --> 00:30:45,811
because when the car
is in the water,

700
00:30:45,905 --> 00:30:46,921
it will start to corrode,

701
00:30:46,999 --> 00:30:48,217
and that attracts all the things

702
00:30:48,241 --> 00:30:49,796
that help the coral grow.

703
00:30:49,905 --> 00:30:51,861
And then the car itself
just rusts away

704
00:30:51,944 --> 00:30:53,363
to absolutely nothing.

705
00:30:53,436 --> 00:30:55,046
So this one, which started life

706
00:30:55,124 --> 00:30:56,397
as a pretty horrible Peugeot

707
00:30:56,444 --> 00:30:57,780
and was always a terrible car,

708
00:30:57,897 --> 00:31:01,046
will eventually become
a beautiful coral reef.

709
00:31:01,202 --> 00:31:03,296
And all this happens
quite quickly.

710
00:31:03,382 --> 00:31:04,616
So in just a few years' time,

711
00:31:04,694 --> 00:31:07,343
the BBC will be able to make
a wildlife documentary

712
00:31:07,444 --> 00:31:08,978
just in this wheel arch.

713
00:31:09,003 --> 00:31:10,335
Anyway, we've got the cars.

714
00:31:10,468 --> 00:31:11,468
I've got a crane.

715
00:31:11,538 --> 00:31:12,835
All we need now is a boat,

716
00:31:12,921 --> 00:31:14,577
which is a job
we gave to Jeremy.

717
00:31:14,647 --> 00:31:16,007
That's his responsibility.

718
00:31:16,132 --> 00:31:17,538
He'll have overdone it,
won't he?

719
00:31:17,563 --> 00:31:19,258
Well, he'll have made a
statement of some sort, so...

720
00:31:19,282 --> 00:31:22,725
Freight ship.
Full-on freight ship.

721
00:31:22,773 --> 00:31:24,242
Or a tanker.

722
00:31:30,614 --> 00:31:34,887
♪♪

723
00:31:34,971 --> 00:31:36,639
Oh. He hasn't overdone it.

724
00:31:36,811 --> 00:31:38,746
Is that him?

725
00:31:40,090 --> 00:31:42,301
What is the point of that?

726
00:31:42,574 --> 00:31:44,515
Will you come and tie it up?

727
00:31:49,262 --> 00:31:52,129
That's the worst boat
I've ever seen. That's awful!

728
00:31:52,309 --> 00:31:54,340
- What's the matter with it?
- Well, it...

729
00:31:54,513 --> 00:31:57,473
We gave you $5,000
to buy a boat.

730
00:31:57,559 --> 00:31:59,121
Boats are expensive!

731
00:31:59,228 --> 00:32:01,129
You didn't spend
all five grand on this.

732
00:32:01,232 --> 00:32:02,898
- That is not a five thou...
- Yes!

733
00:32:02,957 --> 00:32:04,551
I've got toothache. Be kind.

734
00:32:04,621 --> 00:32:07,215
Irrelevant.
That is not a $5,000 boat.

735
00:32:07,301 --> 00:32:09,038
- It is!
- It's barely a boat. Look at it!

736
00:32:09,081 --> 00:32:11,426
It's brilliant!
You'll get a car on this.

737
00:32:11,598 --> 00:32:13,762
- Er... Where?
- On the back!

738
00:32:13,863 --> 00:32:15,645
- Who did you buy it from?
- A man.

739
00:32:15,646 --> 00:32:17,848
- Was he laughing?
- No, he wasn't.

740
00:32:17,957 --> 00:32:19,856
- Can I come aboard?
- No.

741
00:32:20,020 --> 00:32:21,220
I don't think it can take two.

742
00:32:21,246 --> 00:32:23,519
Look! It's terrible!

743
00:32:24,009 --> 00:32:25,470
Instead of just standing there,

744
00:32:25,502 --> 00:32:27,697
criticising a man
who's got toothache,

745
00:32:27,963 --> 00:32:31,294
why don't you go and get
a car on the crane

746
00:32:31,365 --> 00:32:33,517
and start loading it?

747
00:32:34,831 --> 00:32:39,306
Soon, our first car was ready
to be lifted onto the boat.

748
00:32:40,197 --> 00:32:42,348
It's just nice to be putting
something back, really.

749
00:32:42,494 --> 00:32:44,439
It genuinely is.
It's a little old Corsa,

750
00:32:44,619 --> 00:32:46,080
and it's gonna be full of coral.

751
00:32:46,197 --> 00:32:47,767
Mr Coral coming, swimming along.

752
00:32:47,845 --> 00:32:49,095
"Ooh, there's something
to latch on to."

753
00:32:49,119 --> 00:32:50,299
Then his friend comes along.

754
00:32:50,377 --> 00:32:51,595
His friend comes along.

755
00:32:51,767 --> 00:32:53,127
This is a genuinely
brilliant idea.

756
00:32:53,166 --> 00:32:55,117
That doesn't fill me with...

757
00:32:55,283 --> 00:32:56,352
total confidence.

758
00:33:03,174 --> 00:33:04,924
Down a bit! Down!

