00:33:05,161 --> 00:33:06,916
You'll have to...

760
00:33:07,130 --> 00:33:08,631
Boom out!

761
00:33:08,799 --> 00:33:10,338
Is that the sign for "boom out"?

762
00:33:10,392 --> 00:33:13,111
That. Yeah, that.

763
00:33:13,299 --> 00:33:15,564
It's like being guided
by The Village People.

764
00:33:15,759 --> 00:33:17,106
It's working now. Unless...

765
00:33:17,158 --> 00:33:19,318
On! On!

766
00:33:19,392 --> 00:33:21,444
- The next danger...
- You're really helping.

767
00:33:21,533 --> 00:33:23,347
- I've got the guideline.
- Right, go!

768
00:33:23,371 --> 00:33:26,902
♪♪

769
00:33:26,949 --> 00:33:29,972
♪♪

770
00:33:30,020 --> 00:33:33,064
- Down a bit, James.
- Watch for the wind.

771
00:33:33,176 --> 00:33:34,692
Hammond,
can you swing it around?

772
00:33:34,717 --> 00:33:35,551
Do you want me to swing it?

773
00:33:35,576 --> 00:33:36,911
Yeah, try and get it...

774
00:33:37,328 --> 00:33:38,901
Oh, shit!

775
00:33:40,531 --> 00:33:42,164
Who pulled that?

776
00:33:42,432 --> 00:33:45,701
We've got to save the car!
It's a reef! Save it!

777
00:33:45,768 --> 00:33:47,570
Oh, it's gone! It's gone!

778
00:33:47,686 --> 00:33:48,912
Who pulled the...

779
00:33:48,996 --> 00:33:51,209
That's to release it,
you Muppet!

780
00:33:51,342 --> 00:33:52,990
Well, I thought
it was a guide rope.

781
00:33:53,115 --> 00:33:56,490
No, I steer it! You just
release it when it's on there!

782
00:33:56,529 --> 00:33:58,420
He told me to steer it without load.

783
00:33:58,506 --> 00:33:59,810
He said,
"Pull the rope to steer it."

784
00:33:59,834 --> 00:34:01,764
This is a £400,000 crane!

785
00:34:01,857 --> 00:34:03,692
Why would you steer it
with a piece of string?!

786
00:34:03,716 --> 00:34:05,076
It's got all these
knobs and buttons.

787
00:34:05,100 --> 00:34:08,391
I steer it, you release it!

788
00:34:08,756 --> 00:34:10,295
So that's a quick release?

789
00:34:10,361 --> 00:34:11,858
- Yes!
- Got it.

790
00:34:14,983 --> 00:34:18,100
What if we just said
we only had four cars?

791
00:34:18,226 --> 00:34:20,570
So we've taken four cars,
removed the engines

792
00:34:20,710 --> 00:34:22,733
and the paint, and they're ready
to go in the sea.

793
00:34:22,827 --> 00:34:25,575
- We'll do that piece to camera again.
- Yeah, yeah.

794
00:34:25,694 --> 00:34:28,538
The thing is, why use a ship
as the hub of your reef?

795
00:34:28,624 --> 00:34:30,554
Why not use cars?
There are millions.

796
00:34:30,679 --> 00:34:33,835
So we've taken four cars,
removed the engines,

797
00:34:33,921 --> 00:34:37,453
stripped them down and they're
ready to go in the sea.

798
00:34:37,624 --> 00:34:39,221
And then James...
Oh, yeah.

799
00:34:39,222 --> 00:34:40,577
And then... And then,

800
00:34:40,687 --> 00:34:42,991
this Peugeot
was no good as a car,

801
00:34:43,124 --> 00:34:46,396
but will be... but the coral
will just stick to it,

802
00:34:46,460 --> 00:34:48,063
oxidising and algae.

803
00:34:48,147 --> 00:34:49,491
Doesn't take very long.

804
00:34:49,569 --> 00:34:52,405
One day, BBC documentary,
wheel arch.

805
00:34:52,499 --> 00:34:54,499
Yeah, from just four cars.
That's all we had.

806
00:34:54,616 --> 00:34:56,572
Four cars. That's all
you need for a reef.

807
00:34:56,663 --> 00:34:58,351
Right, here's the boat
we've selected.

808
00:34:58,393 --> 00:34:59,695
It's a little bit damaged.

809
00:35:01,663 --> 00:35:03,312
With the release rope stowed,

810
00:35:03,429 --> 00:35:06,030
we managed to get
the first of our four cars

811
00:35:06,171 --> 00:35:10,124
onto the boat, which had
come with a broken roof.

812
00:35:11,216 --> 00:35:13,106
Yeah. Oh, yes!

813
00:35:13,289 --> 00:35:15,405
- Yes!
- Yeah!

814
00:35:15,559 --> 00:35:18,193
Good! Result.

815
00:35:18,351 --> 00:35:21,608
And then we had to
secure it in place.

816
00:35:23,476 --> 00:35:25,851
I don't understand
ratchet straps.

817
00:35:25,952 --> 00:35:29,046
Er... There's water
coming into the boat.

818
00:35:29,072 --> 00:35:32,265
- No, there was some in when I bought it.
- It's leaking.

819
00:35:32,437 --> 00:35:34,741
There's always a bit of water
in the bilges.

820
00:35:34,827 --> 00:35:36,874
It's why boats have bilge pumps.

821
00:35:36,976 --> 00:35:38,714
No, it's coming in.

822
00:35:38,937 --> 00:35:41,702
It's not just like it's in,
it's coming in.

823
00:35:41,874 --> 00:35:43,827
- Well, there's none here.
- There's holes! It's leaking!

824
00:35:43,851 --> 00:35:47,569
Oh, shit! No, there is!
Well, attach us to the crane.

825
00:35:47,624 --> 00:35:49,459
Er...
It's gone down.

826
00:35:49,530 --> 00:35:51,491
It has gone...
It is going down.

827
00:35:51,562 --> 00:35:53,171
If you attach us
to the crane,

828
00:35:53,272 --> 00:35:54,564
it won't sink, will it?

829
00:35:54,655 --> 00:35:55,991
We're tied on.

830
00:35:56,069 --> 00:35:58,843
James, can you
just take the slack?

831
00:35:59,905 --> 00:36:01,737
Sadly, James misunderstood

832
00:36:01,796 --> 00:36:03,358
this simple instruction.

833
00:36:03,616 --> 00:36:05,116
Oh, the whole thing

834
00:36:05,208 --> 00:36:06,476
has collapsed at the back!

835
00:36:06,477 --> 00:36:07,810
Oh, dear God!

836
00:36:07,944 --> 00:36:09,712
Wait! Stop!
Whoa! Whoa! What?

837
00:36:09,796 --> 00:36:10,991
It's falling over!

838
00:36:11,101 --> 00:36:12,733
James, it's falling!

839
00:36:12,783 --> 00:36:14,272
- What do you want?
- Holy Mother of God!

840
00:36:14,296 --> 00:36:17,772
It's going down!
Abandon ship! Save yourself!

841
00:36:21,453 --> 00:36:22,986
Catch it, James!

842
00:36:23,026 --> 00:36:24,640
Save it!

843
00:36:24,795 --> 00:36:25,897
Stop!

844
00:36:26,007 --> 00:36:27,858
What are you doing?

845
00:36:27,998 --> 00:36:29,601
Oh, God.

846
00:36:29,766 --> 00:36:31,749
The French Secret Service

847
00:36:31,868 --> 00:36:35,397
didn't do a job as good as this.

848
00:36:35,506 --> 00:36:37,139
I'm not talking
to any of you.

849
00:36:37,226 --> 00:36:39,015
No. Come on,
it was May's fault.

850
00:36:39,075 --> 00:36:40,510
You bought a crap boat,

851
00:36:40,554 --> 00:36:42,488
you put an idiot spaniel
on the crane,

852
00:36:42,513 --> 00:36:44,514
and, also, think
what we were gonna do

853
00:36:44,546 --> 00:36:45,881
for the conception of the car.

854
00:36:45,968 --> 00:36:47,522
People would love the car.
They would see it

855
00:36:47,546 --> 00:36:50,720
as a friendly,
coral-loving thing.

856
00:36:50,976 --> 00:36:52,327
You're swimming
like an old woman.

857
00:36:52,366 --> 00:36:54,749
I don't like being
in the bloody water!

858
00:36:54,825 --> 00:36:59,663
Fact! I'm not comfortable!
I'm from Birmingham!

859
00:36:59,796 --> 00:37:02,031
Having sunk a boat and two cars

860
00:37:02,101 --> 00:37:04,133
where the cruise liners
normally park,

861
00:37:04,218 --> 00:37:09,077
the port authorities
suggested we go away.

862
00:37:09,319 --> 00:37:11,507
So we took
our three remaining cars

863
00:37:11,593 --> 00:37:13,060
to a nearby marina,

864
00:37:13,273 --> 00:37:14,774
built ourselves a raft,

865
00:37:14,897 --> 00:37:16,093
and hired a boat

866
00:37:16,157 --> 00:37:18,429
which had a crane on the front.

867
00:37:22,569 --> 00:37:23,921
- May!
- What?

868
00:37:23,999 --> 00:37:26,124
You're not operating the crane.

869
00:37:26,272 --> 00:37:28,507
You are operating the crane.

870
00:37:28,592 --> 00:37:29,592
Yeah.

871
00:37:29,626 --> 00:37:30,780
I'd just like to point out

872
00:37:30,827 --> 00:37:32,132
that I've been fired from a job

873
00:37:32,186 --> 00:37:33,694
that I was doing perfectly.

874
00:37:34,592 --> 00:37:35,765
Meant that.

875
00:37:35,790 --> 00:37:38,194
I can't get the crane
working. Is there a switch?

876
00:37:38,224 --> 00:37:40,195
Oh! Don't come to me for help.
I'm rubbish at cranes.

877
00:37:40,219 --> 00:37:43,210
I didn't, did I? Did I?

878
00:37:43,719 --> 00:37:46,655
Soon, we were ready
to load our first car.

879
00:37:48,278 --> 00:37:49,344
You're miles away!

880
00:37:49,405 --> 00:37:50,445
You've got to be spot-on.

881
00:37:50,507 --> 00:37:51,914
I can only lift it to there.

882
00:37:51,991 --> 00:37:53,851
This way, this way,
this way, this way.

883
00:37:54,016 --> 00:37:55,726
No, up, up, up.

884
00:37:56,608 --> 00:37:58,507
I can't... Jeremy,
you'll have to go back.

885
00:37:58,577 --> 00:38:00,890
I can't do it if you keep
moving the boat!

886
00:38:00,937 --> 00:38:03,425
If I want to go backwards,
I should go that way.

887
00:38:03,569 --> 00:38:04,914
Right, this way. You've
got to...

888
00:38:04,938 --> 00:38:05,984
- I can't move it...
- I can't go

889
00:38:06,008 --> 00:38:07,177
that way! He's driving!

890
00:38:07,202 --> 00:38:08,757
I can't move it!

891
00:38:08,865 --> 00:38:11,155
Why don't we pick it...
Oh, God.

892
00:38:13,312 --> 00:38:14,921
Where are we going?!

893
00:38:14,983 --> 00:38:17,937
It-Its the bad things...
It's the wind!

894
00:38:18,124 --> 00:38:19,733
Why are we over here?

895
00:38:19,843 --> 00:38:20,943
Wind!

896
00:38:21,022 --> 00:38:23,640
Here he comes!
This is it! This is it!

897
00:38:23,680 --> 00:38:25,715
We're coming in hot!

898
00:38:25,873 --> 00:38:27,544
- Stop... chasing me...
- May, will you do some...

899
00:38:27,568 --> 00:38:29,373
- with the bloody crane!
- thing quickly in your life?

900
00:38:29,397 --> 00:38:31,115
I'm going to kill him!

901
00:38:31,482 --> 00:38:33,967
Here we go! Yes!
Run away! Run away!

902
00:38:34,959 --> 00:38:37,193
We have hooked the apple!

903
00:38:39,201 --> 00:38:41,041
- In a bit, in a bit.
- We are good.

904
00:38:41,107 --> 00:38:43,740
We are so good,
it's almost incredible.

905
00:38:43,764 --> 00:38:45,701
♪♪

906
00:38:45,702 --> 00:38:47,654
Now we had our eye in...

907
00:38:50,104 --> 00:38:51,440
Oh, Jesus.

908
00:38:51,675 --> 00:38:55,945
Loading the second car
was the work of a moment.

909
00:38:55,946 --> 00:38:58,014
- We're on.
- Oh, my God! Yes.

910
00:38:59,515 --> 00:39:01,817
That's it. That'll do.

911
00:39:01,868 --> 00:39:05,040
This is the manliest thing
I've ever done.

912
00:39:05,250 --> 00:39:08,290
I'm just gonna rest
my big balls on my crane.

913
00:39:14,235 --> 00:39:15,671
With our raft full,

914
00:39:15,711 --> 00:39:17,111
we headed out to the spot

915
00:39:17,143 --> 00:39:19,485
identified by marine biologists

916
00:39:19,555 --> 00:39:23,329
as having the perfect depth,
current and temperature

917
00:39:23,439 --> 00:39:25,360
for a reef to form.

918
00:39:26,511 --> 00:39:28,046
Release the reef!

919
00:39:28,078 --> 00:39:30,379
- Yes!
- There it goes!

920
00:39:30,462 --> 00:39:32,571
- The reef is born!
- That's our reef!

921
00:39:32,683 --> 00:39:35,009
- Sink!
- Come, coral! Come!

922
00:39:35,196 --> 00:39:38,415
Yeah!

923
00:39:38,571 --> 00:39:40,673
- Go!
- Yes!

924
00:39:40,791 --> 00:39:43,509
Oh, I'm pleased with that!

925
00:39:43,694 --> 00:39:45,861
The Peugeot 206.

926
00:39:45,955 --> 00:39:47,290
That is brilliant.

927
00:39:49,470 --> 00:39:51,485
Next, we had to anchor
the cars in place,

928
00:39:51,610 --> 00:39:55,813
which was a job for the only
qualified diver among us.

929
00:39:55,939 --> 00:39:58,259
He'd even brought
his own equipment.

930
00:39:59,819 --> 00:40:01,579
Right. Back a bit.

931
00:40:01,611 --> 00:40:02,720
Back... That's on my nose.

932
00:40:02,779 --> 00:40:04,279
Stop moaning!

933
00:40:04,350 --> 00:40:05,579
Ow!

934
00:40:17,415 --> 00:40:18,759
If he were a heart surgeon,

935
00:40:18,891 --> 00:40:20,634
he would turn up
with an old leather bag

936
00:40:20,720 --> 00:40:22,431
with a saw and hammer in it,
wouldn't he?

937
00:40:22,463 --> 00:40:24,290
"I'm ready to do your
operation. Here I am."

938
00:40:28,638 --> 00:40:31,595
It's like his old table with
his Bakelite telephone on it.

939
00:40:31,809 --> 00:40:34,412
- Yes.
- "Hello. Hammersmith 37 here."

940
00:40:35,812 --> 00:40:37,610
James's suit was so old,

941
00:40:37,735 --> 00:40:40,649
it didn't come with
air tanks, so, annoyingly,

942
00:40:40,735 --> 00:40:43,805
it was our responsibility
to keep him alive.

943
00:40:45,856 --> 00:40:47,891
How long
have we got to do this for?

944
00:40:48,251 --> 00:40:50,353
Well, for as long
as he's done there.

945
00:40:50,674 --> 00:40:53,665
- Honestly, I'm exhausted.
- I'm getting dizzy.

946
00:40:54,470 --> 00:40:56,104
We should keep going.

947
00:40:56,199 --> 00:40:58,149
No. Look, there's a generator.

948
00:40:58,268 --> 00:41:00,335
Why don't we just
connect it to the generator?

949
00:41:07,125 --> 00:41:08,510
Now. Now.

950
00:41:08,565 --> 00:41:10,266
- Yeah.
- You're an idiot.

951
00:41:15,762 --> 00:41:17,997
Life-saving air.

952
00:41:18,872 --> 00:41:20,546
Oh, there we go.

953
00:41:21,205 --> 00:41:23,444
On. And relax.

954
00:41:41,469 --> 00:41:42,889
Nearly!

955
00:42:10,740 --> 00:42:12,888
Come in, James.

956
00:42:13,076 --> 00:42:15,896
When our colleague
finally surfaced...

957
00:42:16,146 --> 00:42:18,148
he was very angry.

958
00:42:19,429 --> 00:42:21,730
That was nowhere near
the cars. Nowhere near.

959
00:42:21,802 --> 00:42:23,637
What was nowhere near the cars?

960
00:42:23,748 --> 00:42:26,228
You might as well have dropped
me off the coast of Los Angeles!

961
00:42:26,295 --> 00:42:28,849
- I couldn't even see them!
- Just stop. Stop.

962
00:42:28,892 --> 00:42:30,497
What do you...
What do you mean?

963
00:42:30,638 --> 00:42:32,419
How did you manage...
You're the boat expert,

964
00:42:32,474 --> 00:42:33,559
as you're forever telling us.

965
00:42:33,583 --> 00:42:35,330
How did you manage
to put the cars there

966
00:42:35,427 --> 00:42:38,185
and then move the boat
about 100 yards away?

967
00:42:38,287 --> 00:42:39,311
- We drifted.
- We drifted a bit.

968
00:42:39,335 --> 00:42:41,865
- Have you done the job?
- No.

969
00:42:42,037 --> 00:42:44,099
- What?
- The cars are not anchored.

970
00:42:44,153 --> 00:42:45,466
Because when I got there,

971
00:42:45,567 --> 00:42:48,686
your drifting, stupid,
orange biscuit-tin boat

972
00:42:48,724 --> 00:42:50,146
yanked me back off it!

973
00:42:50,255 --> 00:42:51,708
We don't have an afternoon

974
00:42:51,787 --> 00:42:53,283
to just throw away
while you go paddling.

975
00:42:53,307 --> 00:42:56,076
You're saying... I'm gonna
have to do it, aren't I?

976
00:42:56,100 --> 00:42:57,887
♪♪

977
00:42:57,888 --> 00:43:01,992
Soon, James Bond
was ready to go in the water.

978
00:43:02,016 --> 00:43:04,016
♪♪

979
00:43:04,060 --> 00:43:05,983
- Do I look like Roger Moore?
- Yeah, you do.

980
00:43:06,049 --> 00:43:08,918
- You do, yeah. Yeah.
- Roger Moore, the greengrocer.

981
00:43:09,194 --> 00:43:12,601
- Let go. Yes!
- Yay!

982
00:43:12,913 --> 00:43:15,725
I've just handed
Jeremy a welding iron.

983
00:43:15,795 --> 00:43:17,631
Oh, dear God.

984
00:43:21,978 --> 00:43:25,170
I'm not sure I trust Jeremy
to do welding.

985
00:43:25,467 --> 00:43:27,124
I wouldn't trust Jeremy

986
00:43:27,217 --> 00:43:30,389
to watch a YouTube guide
to welding.

987
00:43:30,520 --> 00:43:33,655
- Oh!
- What's that?

988
00:43:33,772 --> 00:43:36,158
- That's gone wrong.
- Jeremy?

989
00:43:36,268 --> 00:43:38,678
Badly, horribly wrong.

990
00:43:44,334 --> 00:43:46,343
Ah!

991
00:43:46,585 --> 00:43:48,593
- How did that go?
- Very well.

992
00:43:48,780 --> 00:43:50,069
- Did it?
- Oh, yeah.

993
00:43:50,155 --> 00:43:51,139
- Did it?
- Yeah.

994
00:43:51,171 --> 00:43:52,155
That was all...

995
00:43:52,180 --> 00:43:54,686
They are not going
anywhere in a hurry.

996
00:43:54,710 --> 00:43:58,647
♪♪

997
00:43:58,757 --> 00:44:01,550
We headed back to shore
for an agreeable dinner,

998
00:44:01,655 --> 00:44:04,554
happy that our important
environmental work

999
00:44:04,671 --> 00:44:07,241
was, at last, going well.

1000
00:44:08,663 --> 00:44:11,319
♪♪

1001
00:44:11,427 --> 00:44:15,077
But are the coral starting now?

1002
00:44:15,413 --> 00:44:17,030
- Yeah.
- So they're down there now.

1003
00:44:17,085 --> 00:44:20,319
- A bit of coral's gonna...
- Yeah, it will have done.

1004
00:44:20,475 --> 00:44:21,718
It's not a big coral reef,

1005
00:44:21,796 --> 00:44:23,593
but it's the start
of a coral reef.

1006
00:44:23,639 --> 00:44:25,654
Well done, chaps.
We have done...

1007
00:44:25,679 --> 00:44:27,155
I don't clink glasses,
as you know,

1008
00:44:27,186 --> 00:44:29,741
but we can raise a glass
to our success today.

1009
00:44:29,827 --> 00:44:31,389
Yes. Well done, us.

1010
00:44:34,450 --> 00:44:36,418
Maybe that's what
Volkswagen were doing...

1011
00:44:36,419 --> 00:44:37,486
building a reef.

1012
00:44:37,487 --> 00:44:39,654
That could be it.
That could be it.

1013
00:44:39,868 --> 00:44:43,458
We're gonna pick up our important
marine biology work later on.

1014
00:44:43,548 --> 00:44:47,548
But now it's time to play
Celebrity Brain Crash!

1015
00:44:49,692 --> 00:44:53,118
♪♪

1016
00:44:54,930 --> 00:44:56,454
That doesn't get any better.

1017
00:44:56,602 --> 00:44:58,406
That really doesn't get
any better, that sting.

1018
00:44:58,430 --> 00:45:01,688
But anyway,
my guest tonight is from...

1019
00:45:01,735 --> 00:45:03,422
Well, how can I describe it,
really?

1020
00:45:03,501 --> 00:45:04,782
The second biggest

1021
00:45:04,837 --> 00:45:06,448
and most important
part of the world,

1022
00:45:06,508 --> 00:45:09,860
as far as music is concerned:
the Northeast of England.

1023
00:45:09,885 --> 00:45:11,451
Oh, come on!

1024
00:45:11,524 --> 00:45:12,790
Well, hello?!

1025
00:45:12,852 --> 00:45:14,652
Mark Knopfler, Paul Rodgers,

1026
00:45:14,985 --> 00:45:17,792
Gordon Sting, a couple of
people out of Little Mix.

1027
00:45:17,829 --> 00:45:20,562
- Lindisfarne. Mm, lovely.
- Yes, Lindisfarne. We'll gloss over that.

1028
00:45:20,594 --> 00:45:23,359
But then we've also got...
...the main man.

1029
00:45:23,438 --> 00:45:26,969
The man we have lined up for
you, he is the lead singer

1030
00:45:27,037 --> 00:45:29,774
of the biggest Rock Band
in the world, AC/DC.

1031
00:45:29,946 --> 00:45:32,507
Ladies and gentlemen,
Brian Johnson!

1032
00:45:34,555 --> 00:45:35,913
- There he is!
- There he is!

1033
00:45:35,937 --> 00:45:37,375
There he is! Here he comes!

1034
00:45:37,446 --> 00:45:40,188
What are we gonna
talk to him about?

1035
00:45:40,250 --> 00:45:42,626
- Well, he's taken up motor racing.
- Yeah.

1036
00:45:42,766 --> 00:45:44,876
- He's got a new TV show.
- Yes, on the road.

1037
00:45:44,901 --> 00:45:45,856
He's on the road.

1038
00:45:45,881 --> 00:45:48,141
I'm gonna talk to him
about being at the front

1039
00:45:48,212 --> 00:45:50,059
of the world's
biggest Rock Band.

1040
00:45:50,126 --> 00:45:52,016
- Where is he?
- He's Brian Johnson.

1041
00:45:52,086 --> 00:45:53,758
- Here he comes!
- Oh, there he is!

1042
00:45:53,829 --> 00:45:56,587
- There he is.
- The man himself. What a legend!

1043
00:45:56,688 --> 00:45:59,165
I can't... I've always wanted
to meet him. I'm thrilled.

1044
00:45:59,211 --> 00:46:01,184
- Yeah.
- That is a legend. Proper...

1045
00:46:01,270 --> 00:46:02,692
- Oh, hello.
- Oh, hello.

1046
00:46:02,785 --> 00:46:03,872
- What?
- Oh, my...

1047
00:46:05,675 --> 00:46:06,975
Oh, God!

1048
00:46:09,652 --> 00:46:12,457
- We killed him.
- We've killed Brian Johnson.

1049
00:46:12,608 --> 00:46:14,324
That's...

1050
00:46:14,910 --> 00:46:16,668
OK.

1051
00:46:16,952 --> 00:46:18,637
Brian Johnson has been run over

1052
00:46:18,715 --> 00:46:21,731
by some people who think
they are playing football.

1053
00:46:21,801 --> 00:46:23,892
- But they're not.
- It's not football, is it?

1054
00:46:23,934 --> 00:46:25,134
Cos they don't use their feet.

1055
00:46:25,225 --> 00:46:27,043
That's not football.

1056
00:46:27,176 --> 00:46:29,402
That's just people dressing up.

1057
00:46:30,966 --> 00:46:32,367
- That's...
- We play football.

1058
00:46:32,392 --> 00:46:34,621
- We play football.
- Yeah, with our feet.

1059
00:46:34,949 --> 00:46:36,457
We play football.

1060
00:46:36,645 --> 00:46:37,916
- Soccer! It's soccer!
- What?!

1061
00:46:37,940 --> 00:46:40,817
It's not soccer!
It's football that we play!

1062
00:46:40,895 --> 00:46:44,660
It's 6.75 billion people in
the world call it football!

1063
00:46:46,035 --> 00:46:47,746
You can moan and shout
all you like.

1064
00:46:47,832 --> 00:46:49,752
The fact is, we're British
and we edit this show,

1065
00:46:49,824 --> 00:46:51,120
and you'll just get cut out.

1066
00:46:51,246 --> 00:46:52,647
You will.

1067
00:46:53,423 --> 00:46:55,190
This is a rugby ball!

1068
00:46:55,254 --> 00:46:56,391
Look on the screen.

1069
00:46:56,473 --> 00:46:57,645
They're only playing

1070
00:46:57,670 --> 00:47:00,004
with the padding
they were born with!

1071
00:47:00,262 --> 00:47:01,754
This is not a football!

1072
00:47:01,864 --> 00:47:03,698
They call it football.

1073
00:47:07,603 --> 00:47:11,841
USA! USA! USA! USA! USA!

1074
00:47:14,411 --> 00:47:15,615
So...

1075
00:47:15,701 --> 00:47:18,755
Brian Johnson
has been run over by erm...

1076
00:47:18,966 --> 00:47:21,883
some supremely brave
and talented footballers.

1077
00:47:26,923 --> 00:47:28,900
Er...

1078
00:47:29,228 --> 00:47:31,197
Does that mean
he's not coming on, then?

1079
00:47:31,261 --> 00:47:33,275
Well, James, he's been hammered

1080
00:47:33,345 --> 00:47:34,517
to the thickness of an envelope

1081
00:47:34,541 --> 00:47:37,332
and his spine is now
a jigsaw, so that is a no.

1082
00:47:37,392 --> 00:47:38,727
Fine.

1083
00:47:39,166 --> 00:47:41,127
Right, so what are we
gonna do to fill the time?

1084
00:47:41,171 --> 00:47:42,033
I've got nothing.

1085
00:47:42,064 --> 00:47:43,015
We could get back

1086
00:47:43,040 --> 00:47:45,103
to our important
marine biology work.

1087
00:47:45,202 --> 00:47:46,845
- Plan. Do it.
- Yes, let's do that.

1088
00:47:46,900 --> 00:47:48,386
So when we left the action,

1089
00:47:48,486 --> 00:47:50,579
erm... I'd successfully

1090
00:47:50,681 --> 00:47:52,923
welded two cars to the seabed,

1091
00:47:52,970 --> 00:47:54,205
and that was good.

1092
00:47:54,259 --> 00:47:57,061
Yeah, and we pick up
the action the next day,

1093
00:47:57,158 --> 00:47:59,589
as we go back to finish the job.

1094
00:47:59,613 --> 00:48:02,946
♪♪

1095
00:48:03,055 --> 00:48:04,977
On our way
to get the last car,

1096
00:48:05,042 --> 00:48:06,470
we stopped at the reef site

1097
00:48:06,518 --> 00:48:09,055
to make sure everything was OK.

1098
00:48:10,484 --> 00:48:12,087
Tom Daley!

1099
00:48:19,161 --> 00:48:20,794
I don't like it.

1100
00:48:20,843 --> 00:48:22,445
Oh. Oh.

1101
00:48:25,548 --> 00:48:28,101
And after a few moments
in the water,

1102
00:48:28,218 --> 00:48:31,019
we discovered it wasn't.

1103
00:48:31,044 --> 00:48:34,166
Where the bloody hell
are they? There's the buoy.

1104
00:48:34,224 --> 00:48:35,859
This is the wrong place.

1105
00:48:35,953 --> 00:48:37,734
Yes,
that marks the spot.

1106
00:48:37,851 --> 00:48:39,470
They're just not here.

1107
00:48:39,554 --> 00:48:42,640
Why did we trust you
to fix them in place?

1108
00:48:42,665 --> 00:48:44,899
- I didn't... Listen.
- Of all people.

1109
00:48:44,937 --> 00:48:46,195
Well, I don't understand it,

1110
00:48:46,257 --> 00:48:48,882
cos I don't normally
make a mess of...

1111
00:48:48,961 --> 00:48:50,588
Oh, you must have made
a good job of it.

1112
00:48:50,613 --> 00:48:51,844
That's why they've gone!

1113
00:48:51,976 --> 00:48:54,203
There is evidence,
or a lack of it,

1114
00:48:54,398 --> 00:48:55,733
to suggest you can't weld.

1115
00:48:55,758 --> 00:48:57,412
- Oh, shit.
- Maybe a shark...

1116
00:48:57,413 --> 00:48:59,481
- Er...
- What?

1117
00:48:59,711 --> 00:49:01,562
- What?
- Look.

1118
00:49:01,927 --> 00:49:03,445
Oh, brilliant!

1119
00:49:03,519 --> 00:49:05,280
How the hell
did they do that, though?

1120
00:49:05,367 --> 00:49:07,929
You know this current
that's whizzing us about?

1121
00:49:08,023 --> 00:49:10,664
Look at them! They're not
gonna make a reef, are they?!

1122
00:49:10,819 --> 00:49:12,656
Well, maybe... it could be

1123
00:49:12,695 --> 00:49:14,765
like a play area
for the privileged.

1124
00:49:14,824 --> 00:49:15,937
Some rusty cars?

1125
00:49:15,962 --> 00:49:16,944
That doesn't
work, does it?

1126
00:49:16,969 --> 00:49:18,359
No.

1127
00:49:18,383 --> 00:49:21,446
♪♪

1128
00:49:21,471 --> 00:49:23,605
Obviously,
we had to retrieve them,

1129
00:49:23,648 --> 00:49:25,281
which meant moving the raft

1130
00:49:25,341 --> 00:49:28,109
to the stern of our crane boat.

1131
00:49:29,672 --> 00:49:31,304
James,
have you untied that end?

1132
00:49:31,381 --> 00:49:35,398
Yeah. Get ready to catch
this rope. Here we go.

1133
00:49:35,914 --> 00:49:38,265
Pull it along a bit and get
it sort of squared up.

1134
00:49:38,500 --> 00:49:39,788
I'll have a nice ride.

1135
00:49:39,851 --> 00:49:42,476
Right.
Repositioning raft.

1136
00:49:44,664 --> 00:49:46,528
That's a reassuring noise.

1137
00:49:46,648 --> 00:49:50,508
Er... Where...
Where's that come from?

1138
00:49:50,711 --> 00:49:52,066
James. James.

1139
00:49:52,195 --> 00:49:53,734
- What?
- What's that doing over there?

1140
00:49:53,789 --> 00:49:54,844
What's what doing?

1141
00:49:54,992 --> 00:49:56,719
All this bamboo's come off.

1142
00:49:56,883 --> 00:49:58,320
What have you untied?

1143
00:49:58,374 --> 00:50:00,609
I've untied the piece
of string at the front.

1144
00:50:00,656 --> 00:50:04,846
But, look, half the craft
is disappearing.

1145
00:50:05,461 --> 00:50:07,982
As the raft
was disintegrating fast,

1146
00:50:08,148 --> 00:50:10,752
we had to get it
to shore quickly.

1147
00:50:10,875 --> 00:50:13,156
Firing up the machine!

1148
00:50:15,248 --> 00:50:17,883
Sadly, though,
Jeremy's turn of speed

1149
00:50:18,072 --> 00:50:19,891
only made things worse.

1150
00:50:19,959 --> 00:50:22,126
Power! Power! Come on!

1151
00:50:22,197 --> 00:50:23,499
Slow down!

1152
00:50:24,771 --> 00:50:26,857
It's falling apart!

1153
00:50:27,169 --> 00:50:29,505
- Look, he's going down!
- Slow down!

1154
00:50:29,687 --> 00:50:32,156
Slow!

1155
00:50:40,208 --> 00:50:42,584
You can't put cars
on that, can you?

1156
00:50:43,278 --> 00:50:45,435
After we'd rescued James,

1157
00:50:45,521 --> 00:50:48,068
he stupidly suggested that,
to solve the problem,

1158
00:50:48,216 --> 00:50:50,802
we should ruin
everyone's holiday.

1159
00:51:00,866 --> 00:51:03,624
I think these people
should move out of the way.

1160
00:51:03,819 --> 00:51:06,808
My plan was to tow the cars
off the beach

1161
00:51:06,866 --> 00:51:10,379
and back to the harbour
so we could start again.

1162
00:51:10,546 --> 00:51:14,444
Which meant I'd need the help
of the man from Atlantis.

1163
00:51:14,694 --> 00:51:17,486
Hold my hand! There! There!
There! Now, let me go.

1164
00:51:17,487 --> 00:51:19,130
Yeah, that's me.
You have to let...

1165
00:51:19,169 --> 00:51:22,223
Oh, mind my arm!
Let me go now. I'm fine.

1166
00:51:22,504 --> 00:51:23,903
I don't like it!

1167
00:51:27,805 --> 00:51:29,440
Move!

1168
00:51:36,776 --> 00:51:40,323
Hammond, tie both of them to
this and give me a thumbs up.

1169
00:51:40,432 --> 00:51:42,346
If James gets those
onto the road,

1170
00:51:42,440 --> 00:51:44,120
all the way back up to
the harbour,

1171
00:51:44,229 --> 00:51:47,682
build another raft,
get them loaded on...

1172
00:51:47,846 --> 00:51:50,768
bring them back,
it's gonna take days.

1173
00:51:54,034 --> 00:51:56,143
- OK.
- Don't stand near the back.

1174
00:51:56,214 --> 00:51:57,878
The brakes don't work.

1175
00:52:00,589 --> 00:52:02,258
Yeah!

1176
00:52:15,210 --> 00:52:17,946
- Well, now what?
- That was rubbish.

1177
00:52:19,194 --> 00:52:21,883
I then said we should
use my brilliant boat

1178
00:52:21,936 --> 00:52:24,553
to tow the cars back
to the reef site,

1179
00:52:24,687 --> 00:52:27,389
which would be quicker
and easier.

1180
00:52:32,290 --> 00:52:35,225
They're in the water!

1181
00:52:37,190 --> 00:52:39,251
Ha-ha! Power!

1182
00:52:39,375 --> 00:52:40,931
Power! Come on!

1183
00:52:42,856 --> 00:52:44,290
Yes!

1184
00:52:44,474 --> 00:52:47,176
Eat my boat, James May!

1185
00:52:50,145 --> 00:52:51,279
Come on!

1186
00:52:55,159 --> 00:52:57,495
Victory is the boat's!

1187
00:53:00,355 --> 00:53:03,081
James May's hopeless plan...

1188
00:53:04,393 --> 00:53:05,800
What was that?

1189
00:53:07,663 --> 00:53:10,511
With two rusty Peugeots
in his swimming area

1190
00:53:10,566 --> 00:53:12,768
and his beach furniture
in ruins,

1191
00:53:12,902 --> 00:53:15,097
the hotel manager had had enough

1192
00:53:15,160 --> 00:53:16,979
and ordered us to leave.

1193
00:53:18,774 --> 00:53:22,911
We'd now lost four cars,
a boat and our raft.

1194
00:53:23,183 --> 00:53:26,292
But on the plus side,
we still had one car left,

1195
00:53:26,401 --> 00:53:29,784
and most importantly,
the crane boat.

1196
00:53:30,612 --> 00:53:33,534
But that night,
there was bad news.

1197
00:53:37,760 --> 00:53:41,479
The man who owns it
is not best pleased with us.

1198
00:53:41,745 --> 00:53:44,609
- Because?
- He has off-hired it.

1199
00:53:44,737 --> 00:53:47,536
- We've not got the crane boat?
- No.

1200
00:53:47,698 --> 00:53:51,015
- That was the most useful thing we had.
- Yeah.

1201
00:53:51,128 --> 00:53:54,909
So what can we possibly do
with a Land Rover?

1202
00:53:55,206 --> 00:53:57,425
- Well...
- Well, what?

1203
00:53:57,450 --> 00:53:59,136
If I can be positive...

1204
00:53:59,625 --> 00:54:01,511
The Land Rover's
largely aluminium,

1205
00:54:01,659 --> 00:54:03,995
which is actually even better
for creating a reef.

1206
00:54:04,124 --> 00:54:05,659
- True.
- But it's on the land!

1207
00:54:05,766 --> 00:54:08,034
Yes, it is true.
The Land Rover is...

1208
00:54:08,120 --> 00:54:09,979
It's irrelevant.
We've lost everything else.

1209
00:54:10,027 --> 00:54:12,534
Yes, but it's good if...

1210
00:54:14,564 --> 00:54:16,042
I've had a brainwave.

1211
00:54:16,326 --> 00:54:17,761
Oh, God.

1212
00:54:20,612 --> 00:54:22,580
And so, the next morning,

1213
00:54:22,605 --> 00:54:24,565
the people of Barbados
were treated

1214
00:54:24,608 --> 00:54:26,342
to the magnificent spectacle

1215
00:54:26,641 --> 00:54:29,109
of a Land Rover
gliding majestically

1216
00:54:29,187 --> 00:54:30,859
on a bed of inner tubes

1217
00:54:30,969 --> 00:54:33,582
across the Caribbean Sea.

1218
00:54:33,859 --> 00:54:36,438
Here we are on our final car,
and it's a classic.

1219
00:54:36,602 --> 00:54:38,063
It's a Series I Land Rover.

1220
00:54:38,102 --> 00:54:39,602
No, it's a Series II.

1221
00:54:39,722 --> 00:54:41,602
It's a Series I. The lights
are close together.

1222
00:54:41,664 --> 00:54:43,457
No, it's got the barrel
rolls on the doors.

1223
00:54:43,507 --> 00:54:44,750
It's a Series II.

1224
00:54:44,827 --> 00:54:46,438
- That makes it a Series II?
- Yeah.

1225
00:54:46,516 --> 00:54:48,274
I thought Series Ils
had the lights angled.

1226
00:54:48,406 --> 00:54:49,806
I think we're getting
stuck on this.

1227
00:54:49,899 --> 00:54:51,789
- It's a Land Rover.
- It's an old Land Rover.

1228
00:54:51,852 --> 00:54:52,938
The good thing about it is

1229
00:54:53,038 --> 00:54:55,070
it corrodes much less
quickly than the steel car.

1230
00:54:55,180 --> 00:54:57,914
We've also glued these limestone
tiles to it,

1231
00:54:57,984 --> 00:55:01,953
because porous limestone is
the perfect base, foundation,

1232
00:55:02,102 --> 00:55:03,617
for coral to start a reef.

1233
00:55:03,789 --> 00:55:06,766
This is a coral-reef-making
machine.

1234
00:55:07,016 --> 00:55:10,051
In fact, the only fly
in the ointment

1235
00:55:10,195 --> 00:55:12,953
was its propulsion system.

1236
00:55:13,156 --> 00:55:15,790
- Can I go a bit faster?
- No!

1237
00:55:15,891 --> 00:55:17,926
It's filling with
water the faster you go.

1238
00:55:17,927 --> 00:55:19,360
We'll sink it
in the wrong place.

1239
00:55:19,361 --> 00:55:22,797
This is our last car,
our last chance.

1240
00:55:23,148 --> 00:55:25,875
They're bleating on.
"Oh, don't go too fast!"

1241
00:55:26,015 --> 00:55:28,637
You're going faster
again, Jeremy!

1242
00:55:28,851 --> 00:55:30,601
You're pulling it under!

1243
00:55:31,173 --> 00:55:32,445
Relax!

1244
00:55:32,647 --> 00:55:34,382
Am I
the same species as that?

1245
00:55:34,407 --> 00:55:35,267
No.

1246
00:55:35,307 --> 00:55:37,687
Jeremy, don't sink it

1247
00:55:37,726 --> 00:55:39,548
before we get there!

1248
00:55:39,719 --> 00:55:42,026
Mother of God!
Have you seen that?

1249
00:55:42,180 --> 00:55:43,652
- What?
- Guys, look!

1250
00:55:43,868 --> 00:55:46,856
- Oh, my God!
- Holy cow! Look at it!

1251
00:55:47,957 --> 00:55:49,926
That is phenomenal!

1252
00:55:50,044 --> 00:55:52,044
Yeah! Racing!

1253
00:55:52,137 --> 00:55:54,896
Jeremy, you're going to
sink us! Don't race it!

1254
00:55:54,997 --> 00:55:57,801
Catch the... Oh, I haven't
got time for these two.

1255
00:55:57,967 --> 00:56:01,873
Right. Let's go catch
that sailing boat!

1256
00:56:03,042 --> 00:56:05,111
Oh, brilliant!

1257
00:56:05,135 --> 00:56:09,784
♪♪

1258
